WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.267 --> 00:00:04.000
RONALD SMITH: As you know, because we
just got this subject started

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.500
last time, I'm going to
talk today about ice

00:00:06.500 --> 00:00:07.500
in the climate system.

00:00:07.500 --> 00:00:11.567
Let me just review the
types of ice that

00:00:11.567 --> 00:00:14.500
we'll be speaking about.

00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:17.133
Sea ice, which is
frozen seawater.

00:00:17.133 --> 00:00:23.533
Ice sheets, which there's only
two of those existing today in

00:00:23.533 --> 00:00:24.367
the modern world.

00:00:24.367 --> 00:00:26.333
And that's Greenland
and Antarctica.

00:00:26.333 --> 00:00:27.767
We'll talk about those.

00:00:27.767 --> 00:00:31.467
Later on, next week, when we
talk about climate change,

00:00:31.467 --> 00:00:34.633
I'll describe to you how in
earlier days there were some

00:00:34.633 --> 00:00:35.867
other ice sheets on Earth.

00:00:35.867 --> 00:00:38.167
But at the moment there's
just those two.

00:00:38.167 --> 00:00:40.233
We'll talk about
how they work.

00:00:40.233 --> 00:00:42.633
Glaciers, both coming down
from ice sheets and from

00:00:42.633 --> 00:00:44.367
mountain glaciers.

00:00:44.367 --> 00:00:47.467
Ice shelves, icebergs, and
permanent and seasonal

00:00:47.467 --> 00:00:48.033
snowfields.

00:00:48.033 --> 00:00:51.800
So we'll be going through
those subjects today.

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:53.900
And I mentioned these items
last time, as well.

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:56.767
There are certain important
physical properties that

00:00:56.767 --> 00:01:01.900
you'll need to understand in
order to see--in order to

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:05.633
understand really how ice
behaves on our planet.

00:01:05.633 --> 00:01:07.767
And I won't go through
those again today.

00:01:07.767 --> 00:01:10.233
I went through them at the
beginning--at the end of the

00:01:10.233 --> 00:01:12.167
period last time.

00:01:12.167 --> 00:01:13.800
But just review those.

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:16.400
We'll be discussing
those as we go.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:18.567
So let's start with sea ice.

00:01:23.933 --> 00:01:26.733
And what I've shown you here
are some diagrams that

00:01:26.733 --> 00:01:30.967
illustrate how sea ice changes
with season in the two

00:01:30.967 --> 00:01:31.567
hemispheres.

00:01:31.567 --> 00:01:33.567
Now remember, this is
frozen seawater.

00:01:33.567 --> 00:01:39.733
So about this time of year, late
October, you begin to get

00:01:39.733 --> 00:01:44.500
cold air blowing over the
sea surface in the

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:46.733
high northern latitudes.

00:01:46.733 --> 00:01:49.900
So we'll focus on these
two diagrams.

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:54.100
And as the cold air blows over
the ocean surface, it draws

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:58.000
heat out of the ocean,
cools it down.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.833
When you get the temperature
down to about what?

00:02:00.833 --> 00:02:05.200
Not zero, but about minus two
Celsius, because the salt

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:09.233
depresses the freezing point by
that much, then you start

00:02:09.233 --> 00:02:11.967
to get sea ice forming.

00:02:11.967 --> 00:02:15.767
It starts usually in small
little patches of ice called

00:02:15.767 --> 00:02:16.600
pancake ice.

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:18.200
I'll show you that
in a minute.

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:22.900
And then as the season
progresses, you freeze the

00:02:22.900 --> 00:02:25.967
water in between and
those little pieces

00:02:25.967 --> 00:02:27.133
of ice stick together.

00:02:27.133 --> 00:02:30.100
And a month or two later, you've
got a more or less

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:34.567
continuous layer of sea ice in
these high latitude regions.

00:02:34.567 --> 00:02:37.400
And then during the winter,
it deepens.

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:39.467
In other words, you're drawing
heat out of the bottom and

00:02:39.467 --> 00:02:44.733
you're freezing more ocean
water onto the bottom.

00:02:44.733 --> 00:02:49.033
So the thickness of the
sea ice increases.

00:02:49.033 --> 00:02:52.333
So here we are in September,
which is at the end of the

00:02:52.333 --> 00:02:53.100
warming season.

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:55.333
That would be the minimum
in the sea ice.

00:02:55.333 --> 00:02:58.233
And yet there is some sea
ice remaining from

00:02:58.233 --> 00:03:00.733
the previous year.

00:03:00.733 --> 00:03:03.533
Then we begin to build
new sea ice.

00:03:03.533 --> 00:03:08.367
And about six months later, this
is typically or at least

00:03:08.367 --> 00:03:11.667
was--we'll talk about the fact
that it's changing with time.

00:03:11.667 --> 00:03:15.767
But this is typically how far
sea ice extends at the end of

00:03:15.767 --> 00:03:17.867
the cooling season.

00:03:17.867 --> 00:03:19.633
Then it begins to warm again.

00:03:19.633 --> 00:03:22.100
And over the summer, you melt
away a lot of this.

00:03:22.100 --> 00:03:24.100
And you end up back towards
the minimum.

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:26.967
So there's a big seasonality
in sea ice.

00:03:26.967 --> 00:03:29.867
And this is the way
we understand it.

00:03:29.867 --> 00:03:32.500
In March, when you've got
maximum sea ice, you have a

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:36.200
stream of sea ice coming down on
the east side of Greenland.

00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:39.733
Most of Baffin Bay is
filled with sea ice.

00:03:39.733 --> 00:03:47.000
All of Hudson's Bay and James
Bay is filled with sea ice.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.400
And really, it even comes out a
bit into the North Pacific.

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:54.667
But this area stays generally
free of sea ice.

00:03:54.667 --> 00:03:57.067
And you know why that is,
because you remember that

00:03:57.067 --> 00:04:01.033
the--part of the Gulf Stream
splits off and moves up into

00:04:01.033 --> 00:04:01.567
that region.

00:04:01.567 --> 00:04:06.500
So even at the maximum of sea
ice, you still have open water

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:11.467
along the coast of Norway and
even up here in an area that's

00:04:11.467 --> 00:04:12.700
called North Cape.

00:04:15.633 --> 00:04:18.500
Now, of course, in the southern
hemisphere, the

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:21.200
seasons are reversed.

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:25.867
And so it's in March that you'll
have the minimum of sea

00:04:25.867 --> 00:04:27.867
ice, because that's when you're
at the end of the

00:04:27.867 --> 00:04:29.067
warming season.

00:04:29.067 --> 00:04:31.367
And it pretty much
drops to zero.

00:04:31.367 --> 00:04:34.033
In other words, you have a
little bit of permanent sea

00:04:34.033 --> 00:04:37.000
ice remaining, but really
very little.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.167
And then six months later, at
the end of the cooling season,

00:04:40.167 --> 00:04:43.767
you've grown quite a remarkable
area of sea ice,

00:04:43.767 --> 00:04:47.333
by, again, freezing seawater.

00:04:47.333 --> 00:04:49.600
Later on I'm going to be showing
you what the ice on

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.967
Antarctica is doing.

00:04:51.967 --> 00:04:53.700
We'll talk about ice shelves.

00:04:53.700 --> 00:04:56.467
But keep that distinct from
what we're seeing here.

00:04:56.467 --> 00:05:00.067
This is the frozen seawater,
the sea ice that

00:05:00.067 --> 00:05:02.667
I'm referring to.

00:05:02.667 --> 00:05:03.800
Any questions on that?

00:05:03.800 --> 00:05:04.167
Yes.

00:05:04.167 --> 00:05:06.500
STUDENT: Is it because the Gulf
Stream waters are warmer,

00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:07.900
or they're just moving faster?

00:05:07.900 --> 00:05:09.333
PROFESSOR: They're warmer.

00:05:09.333 --> 00:05:13.400
So even in wintertime, the
temperature of the sea surface

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:19.867
here is about plus three
or plus four Celsius.

00:05:19.867 --> 00:05:22.000
And remember, the freezing
point is minus two.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.467
So you're not going to get
freezing of these waters, even

00:05:25.467 --> 00:05:28.533
though you get terrific
cold winds coming

00:05:28.533 --> 00:05:31.867
off of that sea ice.

00:05:31.867 --> 00:05:34.400
I was on an expedition up there
20 years ago, right at

00:05:34.400 --> 00:05:39.333
the edge of this sea ice,
looking at how that cold wind

00:05:39.333 --> 00:05:42.300
was coming off and trying
to freeze the water.

00:05:42.300 --> 00:05:45.133
But there was so much heat
convecting out of the water

00:05:45.133 --> 00:05:47.700
that you weren't able to
cause any new sea ice

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:49.167
forming in that area.

00:05:49.167 --> 00:05:52.267
So it's the warmth of that Gulf
Stream extension that's

00:05:52.267 --> 00:05:56.733
keeping that free of ice.

00:05:56.733 --> 00:05:57.500
Yes?

00:05:57.500 --> 00:05:58.800
STUDENT: How deep is the ice?

00:05:58.800 --> 00:05:59.833
PROFESSOR: I'll talk about that.

00:05:59.833 --> 00:06:04.033
But typically, it's from--at
the end of the freezing

00:06:04.033 --> 00:06:08.900
season, you can freeze ice
about one meter deep.

00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:12.633
But if you mechanically stack
it up, which happens in some

00:06:12.633 --> 00:06:15.700
parts, you can get it to be
about the height of this room,

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:17.733
three or four meters high.

00:06:17.733 --> 00:06:19.967
So compared to the ocean depth,
it's tiny, just the

00:06:19.967 --> 00:06:21.733
thinnest skin.

00:06:21.733 --> 00:06:25.667
But in terms of real physical
dimensions, I would say maybe

00:06:25.667 --> 00:06:28.600
one meter at the end of the
cooling season, in some cases.

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:30.933
Up to four where the
ice has been

00:06:30.933 --> 00:06:32.567
mechanically crushed and stacked.

00:06:35.900 --> 00:06:38.267
Now I want you to notice
something.

00:06:38.267 --> 00:06:43.533
In the Arctic Ocean, it's
ocean at the North Pole.

00:06:43.533 --> 00:06:45.733
And it's confined by
continent surround.

00:06:45.733 --> 00:06:48.033
And you typically
fill that up.

00:06:48.033 --> 00:06:50.667
And you can't go any further,
of course, because you can't

00:06:50.667 --> 00:06:53.000
make any sea ice
over the land.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:58.367
So if you're going to monitor
this sea ice year by year, the

00:06:58.367 --> 00:07:02.300
way it's typically done in the
Northern Hemisphere is to

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:07.933
monitor the minimum sea ice,
which is in September.

00:07:07.933 --> 00:07:10.533
Maximum wouldn't make much
sense, because you're not

00:07:10.533 --> 00:07:11.833
going to fill that
in with ice.

00:07:11.833 --> 00:07:14.433
And you've already taken
it shore to shore

00:07:14.433 --> 00:07:15.967
in the Arctic Ocean.

00:07:15.967 --> 00:07:19.300
So the way you monitor
interannual variations, or

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:22.867
trends, is to keep track
of the minimum.

00:07:22.867 --> 00:07:26.733
On the other hand, in the
Southern Hemisphere, the

00:07:26.733 --> 00:07:29.600
minimum is pretty much zero.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:34.067
It goes--you have a continent
filling the South Pole.

00:07:34.067 --> 00:07:36.833
And you're not going to form
any sea ice there.

00:07:36.833 --> 00:07:38.600
And the sea ice itself
pretty much goes

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:39.967
back to that shoreline.

00:07:39.967 --> 00:07:45.300
So the way we monitor sea ice
in the Southern Hemisphere

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:50.933
typically is by the maximum
sea ice that you grow.

00:07:50.933 --> 00:07:54.500
Notice, then, that that means
September is kind of the month

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:58.500
where we monitor sea ice in both
hemispheres, even though

00:07:58.500 --> 00:08:02.467
the seasonality is opposite
in the two hemispheres.

00:08:02.467 --> 00:08:03.733
So be aware of that.

00:08:03.733 --> 00:08:06.333
It's a curious way
that we decide to

00:08:06.333 --> 00:08:07.200
monitor these things.

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:09.333
So pancake ice looks
like this.

00:08:09.333 --> 00:08:12.633
So when the winter is beginning,
and the cold air is

00:08:12.633 --> 00:08:18.400
drawing heat out of the ocean,
for a period of some days or

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:22.533
weeks, you have little chunks
of ice that are from half a

00:08:22.533 --> 00:08:25.067
meter to a couple meters
in diameter.

00:08:25.067 --> 00:08:27.600
They have rounded edges, because
with the wave action,

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:29.967
they keep bouncing into
each other breaking

00:08:29.967 --> 00:08:33.467
off any sharp corners.

00:08:33.467 --> 00:08:36.067
And then a few weeks later you
begin to freeze and get a more

00:08:36.067 --> 00:08:37.467
continuous ice.

00:08:37.467 --> 00:08:39.667
This happens to be continuous
sea ice

00:08:39.667 --> 00:08:41.267
with compression ridges.

00:08:41.267 --> 00:08:44.067
In other words, when you look at
these features like this or

00:08:44.067 --> 00:08:48.167
that, that's an area where the
wind has blown the sea ice

00:08:48.167 --> 00:08:53.533
together and it has crumpled
along a line.

00:08:53.533 --> 00:08:59.533
And so if you're traveling over
sea ice, as the early

00:08:59.533 --> 00:09:02.800
explorers were trying to do,
travel over the sea ice to

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:06.800
reach the North Pole, it's not
like some skating rink where

00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:10.633
you can just ski or skate
across the sea ice.

00:09:10.633 --> 00:09:14.667
In fact, every few hundred
meters, you end up climbing

00:09:14.667 --> 00:09:19.167
over one of these compression
ridges, which makes traveling

00:09:19.167 --> 00:09:21.500
there extremely difficult.

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:24.633
You have to pull your sledges or
whatever kind of equipment

00:09:24.633 --> 00:09:27.300
you have up over these
ridges and then down.

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:29.167
You get maybe 50 or 100
yards, and then

00:09:29.167 --> 00:09:30.033
you're doing it again.

00:09:30.033 --> 00:09:32.733
So it's very rough going
when you're trying to

00:09:32.733 --> 00:09:33.533
cross the sea ice.

00:09:33.533 --> 00:09:33.867
Yes?

00:09:33.867 --> 00:09:35.700
STUDENT: How tall do
the ridges get?

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:40.367
PROFESSOR: So the
ridges will get typically only

00:09:40.367 --> 00:09:42.933
four or five meters high.

00:09:42.933 --> 00:09:46.300
But remember, they've got a
root which you don't see.

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:50.000
But in order to support that
extra weight, they also have a

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.533
root that goes down
beneath the ice.

00:09:52.533 --> 00:09:56.300
So if you measured it from top
to bottom, it might be 20 or

00:09:56.300 --> 00:10:00.067
30 meters, but the part you have
to climb over is just 3

00:10:00.067 --> 00:10:01.667
or 4 meters, something
like that.

00:10:01.667 --> 00:10:02.100
Yes?

00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:03.433
STUDENT: How are they formed?

00:10:03.433 --> 00:10:05.300
PROFESSOR: By compression.

00:10:05.300 --> 00:10:08.933
So the wind, for example,
blowing over the ice will try

00:10:08.933 --> 00:10:10.267
to push it.

00:10:10.267 --> 00:10:13.033
But if it comes up against a
shoreline, it can't be pushed

00:10:13.033 --> 00:10:14.167
any further.

00:10:14.167 --> 00:10:17.200
And so you'll end up just
crumpling that ice and

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:20.900
stacking it up along
these ridges.

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:21.233
Yeah.

00:10:21.233 --> 00:10:23.333
Good questions.

00:10:23.333 --> 00:10:27.567
So here's another picture
of sea ice.

00:10:27.567 --> 00:10:30.267
And I wanted to ask you, first
of all, was this picture taken

00:10:30.267 --> 00:10:34.433
in winter or summer
would you guess?

00:10:34.433 --> 00:10:35.200
STUDENT: Summer?

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:36.433
PROFESSOR: Why?

00:10:40.633 --> 00:10:42.100
It was taken in summer.

00:10:42.100 --> 00:10:43.800
How would you know that?

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:45.567
STUDENT: The ice isn't
continuous?

00:10:45.567 --> 00:10:46.033
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:10:46.033 --> 00:10:47.800
STUDENT: So the ice
isn't continuous?

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:47.867
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:10:47.867 --> 00:10:49.867
It's got some melt water
in between here.

00:10:49.867 --> 00:10:52.267
But there's even a more obvious
answer than that.

00:10:52.267 --> 00:10:54.533
STUDENT: Do they hibernate
in the winter?

00:10:54.533 --> 00:10:55.433
PROFESSOR: That's true also.

00:10:55.433 --> 00:10:59.000
But there's even a more obvious
answer than that.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:10:59.600
STUDENT: The sunlight.

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:00.700
PROFESSOR: It's sunlit.

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:01.300
Exactly.

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:03.567
So you could not take a picture
like that in the

00:11:03.567 --> 00:11:04.133
winter time.

00:11:04.133 --> 00:11:05.733
It would be pitch dark.

00:11:05.733 --> 00:11:07.333
So it is true it is melt ice.

00:11:07.333 --> 00:11:09.667
It is true the polar bears
walking around.

00:11:09.667 --> 00:11:13.967
But even more obvious is it's
sunlit, so that means in those

00:11:13.967 --> 00:11:17.400
latitudes that's got to be
a summertime picture.

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:19.700
Just a trick question for
you this morning.

00:11:19.700 --> 00:11:21.067
Seeing if you're awake.

00:11:21.067 --> 00:11:24.867
So let's take a look
at what happens.

00:11:24.867 --> 00:11:27.400
This is a short movie.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:31.333
And it'll just show you remember
the date is up here.

00:11:31.333 --> 00:11:33.567
And you'll watch that change.

00:11:33.567 --> 00:11:37.233
And so we'll just watch
how one season's

00:11:37.233 --> 00:11:39.467
sea ice grows here.

00:11:39.467 --> 00:11:46.467
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:11:46.467 --> 00:11:49.400
PROFESSOR: So it's growing now,

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:50.500
filling out the basin.

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:53.233
Look what's happening
in Hudson's Bay.

00:11:53.233 --> 00:11:55.033
Filling in James Bay too.

00:11:55.033 --> 00:11:56.867
Still growing a bit up here.

00:11:56.867 --> 00:11:59.300
But it's now about as far
as it's going to get.

00:11:59.300 --> 00:12:02.033
A little bit of extra growth
there in Baffin Bay.

00:12:02.033 --> 00:12:04.400
A little bit more growth,
though, in the current

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:05.167
bringing it down.

00:12:05.167 --> 00:12:05.300
[END  VIDEO  PLAYBACK]

00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:06.567
PROFESSOR: And then
there we are in March.

00:12:06.567 --> 00:12:08.367
So that's kind of
at the maximum.

00:12:08.367 --> 00:12:12.700
The movie just takes you from
minimum to maximum last year,

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:16.067
in the year 2010.

00:12:16.067 --> 00:12:18.400
Now what will happen after that,
not shown, is that this

00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:19.633
will all began to melt back.

00:12:19.633 --> 00:12:24.000
And we'll end up back towards
that minimum September

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.267
distribution.

00:12:28.633 --> 00:12:31.067
Let me play that again, just
so you can-- in case you

00:12:31.067 --> 00:12:32.500
missed something.

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:34.367
Every place you look
at you see a little

00:12:34.367 --> 00:12:35.967
different story there.

00:12:35.967 --> 00:12:37.300
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:37.300 --> 00:12:39.300
PROFESSOR: Also, the
