little bit.

00:12:52.133 --> 00:12:54.633
The shade of white gives you
something about the thickness

00:12:54.633 --> 00:12:56.700
or the continuity
of the sea ice.

00:12:56.700 --> 00:13:00.533
If there's gaps, that will show
up as a slightly darker

00:13:00.533 --> 00:13:01.933
shade of gray.

00:13:01.933 --> 00:13:04.800
[END  VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:07.300
PROFESSOR: So Rachel
asked about thickness.

00:13:10.867 --> 00:13:12.900
Here's some examples.

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:16.700
The mean, from 1982 to 2000 now
it's difficult to measure

00:13:16.700 --> 00:13:17.433
ice thickness.

00:13:17.433 --> 00:13:21.000
There are various
ways to do it.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.267
The earliest way was to
take a submarine.

00:13:23.267 --> 00:13:26.667
In the late '60s they finally
got nuclear submarines that

00:13:26.667 --> 00:13:29.000
could pass under
the ice sheet.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:33.200
And then with an up-looking
sonar you could measure the

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:35.700
bottom and the top of the
ice and get a thickness

00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:37.167
measurement that way.

00:13:37.167 --> 00:13:40.100
Of course, you can go there in
situ, but then how do you--you

00:13:40.100 --> 00:13:42.900
want to get some measurement
that's kind of representative

00:13:42.900 --> 00:13:44.267
of a large area.

00:13:44.267 --> 00:13:46.867
It's hard to do that if you're
just walking around on the ice

00:13:46.867 --> 00:13:48.667
with some kind of way
of drilling through.

00:13:48.667 --> 00:13:54.933
So now there's a way to fly over
it, and use down-scanning

00:13:54.933 --> 00:13:58.800
atmospheric acoustic waves or
electromagnetic waves to

00:13:58.800 --> 00:14:00.600
measure sea ice thickness
as well.

00:14:00.600 --> 00:14:02.300
So it's not a perfectly
solved problem.

00:14:02.300 --> 00:14:04.467
But this will give
you some idea.

00:14:04.467 --> 00:14:05.967
The scale is down
on the bottom.

00:14:05.967 --> 00:14:09.067
It's in meters, from zero
to four meters.

00:14:09.067 --> 00:14:13.767
And it's all over on the north
slope of Canada--north slope

00:14:13.767 --> 00:14:17.100
of Alaska and then along the
Canadian Archipelago where you

00:14:17.100 --> 00:14:19.667
get this deeper ice.

00:14:19.667 --> 00:14:24.700
And that, I've made the case for
you, is not you can't grow

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:28.467
ice that thick
thermodynamically, by freezing

00:14:28.467 --> 00:14:28.933
at the bottom.

00:14:28.933 --> 00:14:32.333
Because after it gets to a
certain thickness, remember

00:14:32.333 --> 00:14:34.700
you have to take the
heat out the top.

00:14:34.700 --> 00:14:36.333
That's where the atmosphere
is cold.

00:14:36.333 --> 00:14:39.367
And yet you've got to freeze
the water at the bottom.

00:14:39.367 --> 00:14:42.033
And after a while, it becomes
too hard to get that heat to

00:14:42.033 --> 00:14:44.133
conduct out through that
layer of sea ice.

00:14:44.133 --> 00:14:48.400
So you can only grow sea ice
thermodynamically to this kind

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:49.133
of thickness.

00:14:49.133 --> 00:14:51.733
This is a mechanical
stacking process.

00:14:51.733 --> 00:14:54.200
And you can understand that if
you remember that across the

00:14:54.200 --> 00:14:56.433
Arctic Ocean there is
a current called

00:14:56.433 --> 00:14:58.933
the Transpolar Drift.

00:14:58.933 --> 00:15:00.400
And also the Beaufort Gyre.

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:03.833
But that's going to be carrying
ice and pushing it up

00:15:03.833 --> 00:15:07.000
against the north coast of
Greenland and along the

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:11.033
Canadian Archipelago, and then
causing that compression ridge

00:15:11.033 --> 00:15:13.167
to form, those compression
ridges.

00:15:13.167 --> 00:15:18.567
And that deepens the average ice
thickness to as great as

00:15:18.567 --> 00:15:21.667
four meters, in other words,
typically a little higher than

00:15:21.667 --> 00:15:24.600
the ceiling in this room.

00:15:24.600 --> 00:15:27.867
Questions on that?

00:15:27.867 --> 00:15:33.200
So here's what's been going on
the last couple of decades.

00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:38.367
So this is the Northern
Hemisphere extent anomaly.

00:15:38.367 --> 00:15:42.667
Remember we're learning to
understand this word anomaly,

00:15:42.667 --> 00:15:45.833
because it's often used
in climate analysis.

00:15:45.833 --> 00:15:48.200
What they do is take a
measurement and then subtract

00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:52.367
off a mean value to just
emphasize the changes that

00:15:52.367 --> 00:15:53.400
have occurred.

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:55.567
And this is expressed
in percent.

00:15:55.567 --> 00:15:56.567
And zero is here.

00:15:56.567 --> 00:15:58.300
So they've taken a year.

00:15:58.300 --> 00:16:04.700
They've taken 1979 to the year
2000 as their reference time,

00:16:04.700 --> 00:16:08.867
subtracted off the mean, and
then here's what's left as the

00:16:08.867 --> 00:16:11.100
residual or as the anomaly.

00:16:11.100 --> 00:16:14.800
So basically, in the earlier
part of the time it was--had a

00:16:14.800 --> 00:16:18.433
positive anomaly by definition,
as it's

00:16:18.433 --> 00:16:19.067
decreasing.

00:16:19.067 --> 00:16:21.733
And then near the end you
get a negative anomaly.

00:16:21.733 --> 00:16:25.833
So really the change has
been remarkable.

00:16:25.833 --> 00:16:30.567
Overall that's about a 40% if
you count this, maybe even a

00:16:30.567 --> 00:16:36.267
50% decrease in the area covered
by ice in September.

00:16:36.267 --> 00:16:41.100
That's in the minimum period,
after the warming season.

00:16:41.100 --> 00:16:43.200
There was quite a shock, and
you read about this in the

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:46.767
newspaper perhaps,
back in 2007.

00:16:46.767 --> 00:16:50.533
We had this remarkable drop
in sea ice extent

00:16:50.533 --> 00:16:52.000
in the Arctic Ocean.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:53.700
Then it rebounded.

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:55.000
And people were saying,
well, maybe

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.300
that was just an anomaly.

00:16:56.300 --> 00:16:57.667
Well, it was an anomaly.

00:16:57.667 --> 00:16:59.100
But now it's come down again.

00:16:59.100 --> 00:17:02.333
So the point is it's been
noisy all along.

00:17:02.333 --> 00:17:05.000
But nevertheless the
trend, the downward

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.700
trend is very clear.

00:17:06.700 --> 00:17:08.933
And what I would expect to
happen in the future, it would

00:17:08.933 --> 00:17:13.167
decline further, but be very
noisy from year to year.

00:17:13.167 --> 00:17:16.200
And you can extrapolate
this for yourself.

00:17:16.200 --> 00:17:19.867
In another 20 or 30 years, it
seems like we'll have an

00:17:19.867 --> 00:17:26.600
ice-free Arctic Ocean at the
end of the warming season.

00:17:26.600 --> 00:17:27.833
Questions on that?

00:17:30.067 --> 00:17:35.267
So the Southern Hemisphere,
again September.

00:17:35.267 --> 00:17:37.200
This is the maximum,
because the minimum

00:17:37.200 --> 00:17:38.133
doesn't make any sense.

00:17:38.133 --> 00:17:40.733
It pulls right back pretty
much to the shores of

00:17:40.733 --> 00:17:41.733
Antarctica.

00:17:41.733 --> 00:17:42.900
That's pretty flat.

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:46.067
Or, if you looked at it very
closely, it's even increasing

00:17:46.067 --> 00:17:48.300
ever so slightly.

00:17:48.300 --> 00:17:51.200
And so this trend in sea ice
that we see in the Northern

00:17:51.200 --> 00:17:55.500
Hemisphere is not found in
the Southern Hemisphere.

00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:57.667
When we're talking about things
like global warming,

00:17:57.667 --> 00:18:03.500
we'll come back and refer to
measurements such as this one.

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:05.800
But remember, this has a
somewhat different meaning,

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:09.867
because this is the maximum
extent of sea ice.

00:18:09.867 --> 00:18:13.867
Whereas the other one, for the
Northern Arctic Ocean was the

00:18:13.867 --> 00:18:15.833
minimum extent of sea ice.

00:18:15.833 --> 00:18:17.067
Any questions on that?

00:18:19.467 --> 00:18:24.433
And of course what's also in
the news is that now, as in

00:18:24.433 --> 00:18:29.433
the Arctic Ocean, you get a
retreat of that minimum sea

00:18:29.433 --> 00:18:31.333
ice in September.

00:18:31.333 --> 00:18:36.333
You've opened up these
two long-sought

00:18:36.333 --> 00:18:38.333
navigational routes.

00:18:38.333 --> 00:18:42.533
For years and years in the
17th and 18th and 19th

00:18:42.533 --> 00:18:46.467
centuries, sailors were seeking
the Northwest Passage,

00:18:46.467 --> 00:18:48.700
trying to find a way to get
between the Atlantic and the

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:52.033
Pacific without going all
the way under Cape Horn.

00:18:52.033 --> 00:18:53.867
And this is what they
were trying to do.

00:18:53.867 --> 00:18:56.500
They never achieved it,
but now today you can.

00:18:56.500 --> 00:18:59.567
There is a month or so in the
summer when you can take a

00:18:59.567 --> 00:19:05.233
ship through the Canadian
Archipelago free of ice and

00:19:05.233 --> 00:19:06.700
transport back and forth.

00:19:06.700 --> 00:19:14.133
And in the last well, at least
in 2007, and in this year,

00:19:14.133 --> 00:19:17.233
there's actually a northern
sea route along the north

00:19:17.233 --> 00:19:21.267
coast of Russia that you could
use also to get back and forth

00:19:21.267 --> 00:19:23.333
between the two oceans.

00:19:23.333 --> 00:19:26.900
So navigation is now becoming
possible in the Arctic Ocean.

00:19:26.900 --> 00:19:29.567
And so is things like
oil drilling.

00:19:29.567 --> 00:19:31.933
So there's been a lot of
discussion about who's going

00:19:31.933 --> 00:19:36.833
to lead the charge to now
developing oil resources in

00:19:36.833 --> 00:19:37.900
the Arctic Ocean.

00:19:37.900 --> 00:19:41.967
It's quite a change
going on up there.

00:19:41.967 --> 00:19:43.633
So any questions on sea ice?

00:19:43.633 --> 00:19:46.167
This was all about
frozen seawater.

00:19:46.167 --> 00:19:47.967
Any questions on that?

00:19:47.967 --> 00:19:48.867
Yes, Julia

00:19:48.867 --> 00:19:49.300
STUDENT: Can you quickly review
how the wind--is it

00:19:49.300 --> 00:19:50.567
convection?

00:19:53.267 --> 00:19:54.333
PROFESSOR: Yes,
so the cold wind

00:19:54.333 --> 00:19:55.967
blows over the sea.

00:19:55.967 --> 00:20:00.067
It draws heat out of the ocean,
drops the temperature

00:20:00.067 --> 00:20:03.333
down to zero degrees Celsius,
then below, down

00:20:03.333 --> 00:20:04.833
to minus two Celsius.

00:20:04.833 --> 00:20:07.900
And at that point then,
you start to freeze.

00:20:07.900 --> 00:20:12.233
And of course, I showed you on
the first slide, you've got to

00:20:12.233 --> 00:20:15.267
draw certain amount of heat out
for every kilogram of ice

00:20:15.267 --> 00:20:16.567
that you make.

00:20:16.567 --> 00:20:18.333
That's called the latent
heat of freezing.

00:20:18.333 --> 00:20:21.633
So as you continue to draw
heat out, the temperature

00:20:21.633 --> 00:20:25.067
doesn't drop anymore, but you
continue to build deeper and

00:20:25.067 --> 00:20:26.467
deeper ice.

00:20:26.467 --> 00:20:29.600
So that continues through the
month of March in the Northern

00:20:29.600 --> 00:20:30.867
Hemisphere.

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:39.367
So now we turn to ice sheets,
which is generally defined as

00:20:39.367 --> 00:20:42.833
a large plateau of ice.

00:20:42.833 --> 00:20:46.467
And there's two things
you have to know

00:20:46.467 --> 00:20:47.333
to understand this.

00:20:47.333 --> 00:20:50.267
First of all, on the high
altitude parts of the ice

00:20:50.267 --> 00:20:52.533
sheet this happens to be
Greenland, but it would be the

00:20:52.533 --> 00:20:56.700
same for Antarctica you have
an excess of accumulation

00:20:56.700 --> 00:20:58.233
every year.

00:20:58.233 --> 00:21:03.633
So more snow falls during the
winter than would melt off if

00:21:03.633 --> 00:21:06.400
indeed there's any melt at
all in the summertime.

00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:10.300
And so year after year,
you just accumulate.

00:21:10.300 --> 00:21:11.867
Well, that can't
go on forever.

00:21:11.867 --> 00:21:17.533
I mean, if you accumulated a
meter of snow or 10 meters of

00:21:17.533 --> 00:21:22.000
snow every year, by the time
you got to 10 years or 100

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.067
years or 1,000 years or 10,000
years, you would have an

00:21:25.067 --> 00:21:26.967
enormous pile of snow.

00:21:26.967 --> 00:21:28.600
So you have to balance that.

00:21:28.600 --> 00:21:31.133
And what happens is that,
under its own weight, it

00:21:31.133 --> 00:21:34.667
begins to sag and to flow.

00:21:34.667 --> 00:21:38.900
So the snow gets compressed into
more or less solid ice.

00:21:38.900 --> 00:21:42.733
And then that ice itself, under
high pressure conditions

00:21:42.733 --> 00:21:46.833
with a lot of weight above it,
will begin to flow out toward

00:21:46.833 --> 00:21:49.500
the edges of the continent.

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:52.200
You can simulate this next time
you've got pancakes for

00:21:52.200 --> 00:21:55.633
breakfast. Just keep pouring
that syrup right in the middle

00:21:55.633 --> 00:21:58.233
the pancake, and it
only get so deep.

00:21:58.233 --> 00:22:01.933
After a while it begins
to flow off the edges.

00:22:01.933 --> 00:22:03.200
And that's exactly
what's happening.

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:09.933
It's just gravity forcing that
viscous fluid toward the edges

00:22:09.933 --> 00:22:11.667
of the pancake.

00:22:11.667 --> 00:22:16.000
Then near the edge, there could
be some loss by melting

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.800
or direct sublimation.

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:23.967
Sublimation is when you go
directly from ice to vapor.

00:22:23.967 --> 00:22:26.533
But if that's not sufficient,
then the ice will actually be

00:22:26.533 --> 00:22:29.267
squeezed out and will
reach the ocean.

00:22:29.267 --> 00:22:34.933
And then you'll break off those
chunks as icebergs.

00:22:34.933 --> 00:22:38.067
But in any case, you've got to
balance the mass by having

00:22:38.067 --> 00:22:42.233
this flow moving from the
center towards the edge.

00:22:42.233 --> 00:22:45.667
And that's the way
ice sheets work.

00:22:45.667 --> 00:22:47.233
That speed is not very great.

00:22:47.233 --> 00:22:53.133
It may be only a meter per day
or even a meter per week.

00:22:53.133 --> 00:22:55.467
Those flows can be quite slow.

00:22:55.467 --> 00:23:00.133
But nevertheless, they balance
this annual accumulation of

00:23:00.133 --> 00:23:04.467
snow on the high parts
of the ice sheet.

00:23:04.467 --> 00:23:07.900
You can imagine then, if you
have this spreading going on,

00:23:07.900 --> 00:23:12.033
there has to be some kind of a
divide, just like when we did

00:23:12.033 --> 00:23:16.133
the river trip, we understood
that there is a divide between

00:23:16.133 --> 00:23:17.733
water sheds.

00:23:17.733 --> 00:23:20.767
Rain that falls on one side
goes into one river.

00:23:20.767 --> 00:23:23.300
Rain that falls on the other
side goes into another river.

00:23:23.300 --> 00:23:24.767
The same is true with ice.

00:23:24.767 --> 00:23:27.967
It's called an ice divide, so
that the snowflake that falls

00:23:27.967 --> 00:23:30.967
here will end up being squeezed
out towards the west

00:23:30.967 --> 00:23:31.867
coast of Greenland.

00:23:31.867 --> 00:23:35.333
A snowflake that falls there
will be squeezed out towards

00:23:35.333 --> 00:23:37.467
the east coast and the
north and so on.

00:23:37.467 --> 00:23:39.533
And Antarctica has
similar divides.

00:23:39.533 --> 00:23:41.433
They're drawn here.

00:23:41.433 --> 00:23:43.500
There's quite a number
of them, actually.

00:23:43.500 --> 00:23:47.333
But each snowflake then will
be squeezed out ultimately

00:23:47.333 --> 00:23:51.400
towards one part of the coast
or the other depending where

00:23:51.400 --> 00:23:56.500
they fall relative to
these ice divides.

00:23:56.500 --> 00:23:57.733
Any questions on that?

00:24:01.767 --> 00:24:04.000
So when you're up on the
Greenland ice sheet,

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.467
it looks like this.

00:24:06.467 --> 00:24:09.500
More or less continuous
sheets of deep ice.

00:24:09.500 --> 00:24:13.667
There may be a kilometer or
more of ice beneath you.

00:24:13.667 --> 00:24:15.933
Very deep ice.

00:24:15.933 --> 00:24:19.833
Occasionally you may get a rocky
outcrop, a so-called

00:24:19.833 --> 00:24:22.933
nunatak, where a mountain
ridge sticks

00:24:22.933 --> 00:24:24.667
up through the ice.

00:24:24.667 --> 00:24:27.500
But for the most part, there's
very deep ice, maybe a

00:24:27.500 --> 00:24:31.767
kilometer or two of
ice beneath you.

00:24:31.767 --> 00:24:35.667
And you don't have any sense of
that slow creeping motion,

00:24:35.667 --> 00:24:37.667
at least not here where
it's smooth.

00:24:41.267 --> 00:24:47.033
When the ice squeezes out to the
edge, in some places when

00:24:47.033 --> 00:24:51.500
it reaches the sea it'll
maintain its continuity as an

00:24:51.500 --> 00:24:55.867
ice sheet, but spread out and
begin to float over the sea.

00:24:55.867 --> 00:24:57.967
Those are called ice shelves.

00:24:57.967 --> 00:25:00.467
And I've shown you the dominant
ice shelves here for

00:25:00.467 --> 00:25:01.833
Antarctica.

00:25:01.833 --> 00:25:07.133
There's the Ross ice shelf,
the Ronne, and the Larsen.

00:25:07.133 --> 00:25:10.900
And here's a zoom of the
Antarctic Peninsula showing

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:14.367
the Larsen ice sheet there.

00:25:14.367 --> 00:25:19.900
So while that's floating out
over the ocean surface, do not

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:21.800
confuse it with sea ice.

00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:24.500
It is still compacted snow.

00:25:24.500 --> 00:25:28.667
It's fresh water in compacted
snow that's flowing out and

00:25:28.667 --> 00:25:31.500
floating over the ocean,
being squeezed off the

00:25:31.500 --> 00:25:34.900
continent in that way.

00:25:34.900 --> 00:25:38.767
So it looks like this.

00:25:38.767 --> 00:25:40.867
At least the part you can
see looks like this.

00:25:40.867 --> 00:25:45.033
But remember, there's
another 90% or so.

00:25:45.033 --> 00:25:47.667
Most of it is beneath the
water's surface because of

00:25:47.667 --> 00:25:49.733
buoyancy considerations.

00:25:49.733 --> 00:25:52.400
But that's an example
of an ice shelf, a

00:25:52.400 --> 00:25:53.200
thick layer of ice.

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:55.967
Here's a ship for scale.

00:25:55.967 --> 00:26:00.400
And basically, the ice is
attached to the land.

00:26:00.400 --> 00:26:04.667
But eventually as it flows off
it gets water underneath.

00:26:04.667 --> 00:26:06.000
It floats up.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:10.067
Remember, ice is less dense than
water, so it floats on

00:26:10.067 --> 00:26:14.200
the water and flows on
out as an ice shelf.

00:26:14.200 --> 00:26:18.000
And then eventually it breaks
off to form icebergs.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.800
Questions there?

00:26:20.800 --> 00:26:25.100
Now, back in 19--in 2002, it
was in the news that the

00:26:25.100 --> 00:26:27.800
Larsen ice shelf, or part
of it, had collapsed.

00:26:27.800 --> 00:26:31.167
So here's a sequence of
satellite images.

00:26:31.167 --> 00:26:35.767
January, 2002, February, late
February, and then March.

00:26:35.767 --> 00:26:38.033
So here is the Larsen
ice shelf.

00:26:38.033 --> 00:26:41.167
Remember, that's on the coast
of the Antarctic Peninsula.

00:26:41.167 --> 00:26:43.133
I just showed that to you.

00:26:43.133 --> 00:26:46.667
It looks like there's already
some weakening going on here.

00:26:46.667 --> 00:26:51.167
But then over the next month or
so, most of that broke away

00:26:51.167 --> 00:26:54.833
and floated on off
as icebergs.

00:26:54.833 --> 00:27:00.200
There's some argument in the
scientific literature about

00:27:00.200 --> 00:27:03.867
the significance of the
sudden loss of an

00:27:03.867 --> 00:27:05.233
ice shelf like this.

00:27:05.233 --> 00:27:07.567
Some would say, well, it doesn't
really mean anything,

00:27:07.567 --> 00:27:10.433
because that ice has already
left the continent.

00:27:10.433 --> 00:27:13.533
It's already floating
over the sea.

00:27:13.533 --> 00:27:15.967
And it'll be replaced.

00:27:15.967 --> 00:27:18.267
In other words, in the natural
flow of things, even in a

00:27:18.267 --> 00:27:22.767
steady state climate, this ice
has to be replaced by new ice

00:27:22.767 --> 00:27:24.000
coming off the land.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:28.800
Others would say, no, a
catastrophic loss like this

00:27:28.800 --> 00:27:31.767
will actually have an effect
back over the land.

00:27:31.767 --> 00:27:35.567
And will accelerate the rate at
which glaciers are flowing

00:27:35.567 --> 00:27:37.667
off the land onto the sea.

00:27:37.667 --> 00:27:41.367
So that argument's a little
bit unresolved, but there

00:27:41.367 --> 00:27:44.967
probably is some climatic
significance when you see a

00:27:44.967 --> 00:27:48.000
sudden collapse of an
ice shelf like that.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:52.800
But it can be argued one
way or the other.

00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:54.033
Questions there?

00:27:56.200 --> 00:28:02.033
Greenland doesn't have much
in the way of ice shelves.

00:28:02.033 --> 00:28:03.733
There's glaciers being produced

00:28:03.733 --> 00:28:06.133
all along both coasts.

00:28:06.133 --> 00:28:08.533
But there's an area up here,
called the Petermann Glacier

00:28:08.533 --> 00:28:15.433
that it might be argued has the
nature of an ice shelf.

00:28:15.433 --> 00:28:16.633
There's the Petermann glacier.

00:28:16.633 --> 00:28:18.033
It certainly looks like that.

00:28:18.033 --> 00:28:20.867
It's got a broad,
flat appearance.

00:28:20.867 --> 00:28:24.333
It's floating at this point.

00:28:24.333 --> 00:28:27.467
I'll show you the geometry
of that here.

00:28:27.467 --> 00:28:28.067
So here we are.

00:28:28.067 --> 00:28:31.700
We're up in the northwest
corner of Greenland.

00:28:31.700 --> 00:28:34.100
There's some barren land
with no ice on it.

00:28:34.100 --> 00:28:38.633
But here comes a glacial
stream, coming down

00:28:38.633 --> 00:28:40.933
from the ice sheet.

00:28:40.933 --> 00:28:43.567
And at some point, it does
float out over water.

00:28:43.567 --> 00:28:50.133
And while it is confined to a
fjord, it is floating as a

00:28:50.133 --> 00:28:52.267
more or less continuous
ice sheet.

00:28:52.267 --> 00:28:54.567
And so I guess even though it's
confined, it could be

00:28:54.567 --> 00:28:58.167
called an ice shelf.

00:28:58.167 --> 00:29:01.500
And then it will have a point
where it breaks off and

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:06.200
becomes icebergs
at that point.

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:11.600
And back just last year, in
2010, this was in the news,

00:29:11.600 --> 00:29:15.967
that a big chunk--between July
and August of last year, a big

00:29:15.967 --> 00:29:18.367
chunk of the Petermann
Glacier broke off.

00:29:18.367 --> 00:29:22.867
And then this big flat, huge,
tabular iceberg drifted

00:29:22.867 --> 00:29:29.100
northwest into the Strait of
Nares and ended up blocking

00:29:29.100 --> 00:29:31.767
that channel for a
number of months.

00:29:36.267 --> 00:29:40.400
We're going to right on
to icebergs then.

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:41.167
OK.

00:29:41.167 --> 00:29:43.367
Here's what you need to know.

00:29:43.367 --> 00:29:48.333
The word--the verb for what
happens when you take a

00:29:48.333 --> 00:29:50.833
floating chunk of ice and
break it off to form an

00:29:50.833 --> 00:29:52.700
iceberg is called calve.

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:57.800
So we say that icebergs are
formed from calving.

00:29:57.800 --> 00:29:59.967
That can be either from mountain
glaciers that have

00:29:59.967 --> 00:30:02.833
come down to the sea, or I've
just given you several

00:30:02.833 --> 00:30:07.267
examples of where ice sheet
glaciers come down to the sea.

00:30:07.267 --> 00:30:10.100
And then pieces can break
off to form icebergs.

00:30:10.100 --> 00:30:13.567
Once they're floating, they
drift under the influence of

00:30:13.567 --> 00:30:16.667
wind and ocean currents.

00:30:16.667 --> 00:30:20.433
And don't forget to indicate
that the Coriolis force can

00:30:20.433 --> 00:30:22.100
also play a big role
in this too.

00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:25.600
For example, if the wind pushes
on an iceberg in that

00:30:25.600 --> 00:30:29.600
direction, it'll move
off at right angles.

00:30:29.600 --> 00:30:33.233
So that's because of
the Coriolis force.

00:30:33.233 --> 00:30:37.533
They float with about 90% of
their volume under water.

00:30:37.533 --> 00:30:41.800
We'll work out the math for
that in just a moment.

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:43.900
That means there's a lot
of ice underneath

00:30:43.900 --> 00:30:45.167
that you don't see.

00:30:45.167 --> 00:30:49.200
And if you're in a shallow part
of the ocean, they can

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:52.833
hit the bottom and get stuck.

00:30:52.833 --> 00:30:55.400
So very often you'll find
icebergs that are not moving,

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:57.700
even though the wind is pushing
on them and the

00:30:57.700 --> 00:30:58.967
current is pushing on them.

00:30:58.967 --> 00:31:01.167
But they're just
stuck in place.

00:31:01.167 --> 00:31:04.700
That would have to be because
their bottom is touching.

00:31:04.700 --> 00:31:05.933
So they get stuck there.

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:12.800
They tend to melt the fastest
right around their water line.

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:17.000
Right where the waves splash
up against them you tend to

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.533
get this rapid melting right
around the water line.

00:31:20.533 --> 00:31:24.333
What that will do is change the
shape of these icebergs by

00:31:24.333 --> 00:31:28.467
carving away these grooves
around the water line.

00:31:28.467 --> 00:31:32.133
And at some point, their shape
changes so much that their

00:31:32.133 --> 00:31:35.467
current orientation is
no longer stable.

00:31:35.467 --> 00:31:39.433
And then, without warning, these
things will suddenly

00:31:39.433 --> 00:31:41.100
begin to tip.

00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:45.267
And they'll roll to a new
orientation and then stay that

00:31:45.267 --> 00:31:48.933
way for several weeks while
melting continues around their

00:31:48.933 --> 00:31:51.800
new water line.

00:31:51.800 --> 00:31:53.033
And that's rather remarkable.

00:31:53.033 --> 00:31:56.800
If you get a chance to visit
these latitudes and if you see

00:31:56.800 --> 00:32:00.733
a broad field of icebergs, and
if you're patient and wait a

00:32:00.733 --> 00:32:03.333
few minutes, because there's
so many of them, you'll

00:32:03.333 --> 00:32:06.900
probably see one or two
of them do that roll.

00:32:06.900 --> 00:32:08.533
And that's the reason
why you don't want

00:32:08.533 --> 00:32:09.367
to be close to them.

00:32:09.367 --> 00:32:11.867
Because when they roll, they'll
put off a wave. And

00:32:11.867 --> 00:32:14.467
they would swamp you if you're
in a small boat.

00:32:14.467 --> 00:32:20.200
That'll happen suddenly,
without any warning.

