00:33:56.733 --> 00:33:59.200
So that's the calving process.

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:01.067
So that ice has come out.

00:34:01.067 --> 00:34:03.900
And then eventually it has
to break off pieces.

00:34:03.900 --> 00:34:06.967
And it happens kind
of in a dramatic

00:34:06.967 --> 00:34:10.933
fashion, as you saw there.

00:34:10.933 --> 00:34:15.167
So from that bit of fun to the
mathematics of the situation.

00:34:15.167 --> 00:34:18.000
So remember, Archimedes law.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:19.567
We've talked about it before
in this course.

00:34:19.567 --> 00:34:23.200
It basically says that the
buoyancy force pushing up on a

00:34:23.200 --> 00:34:28.833
submerged obstacle--submerged
object is equal to the weight

00:34:28.833 --> 00:34:32.467
of the fluid displaced.

00:34:32.467 --> 00:34:37.367
So when you have an object like
this, like an iceberg,

00:34:37.367 --> 00:34:40.267
floating in a stable
configuration, there's going

00:34:40.267 --> 00:34:44.500
to be a balance of its own
weight with the buoyancy force

00:34:44.500 --> 00:34:46.033
pushing it up.

00:34:46.033 --> 00:34:48.967
So I've left the acceleration of
gravity off of both terms,

00:34:48.967 --> 00:34:50.833
but that would be the
same in both cases.

00:34:50.833 --> 00:35:00.333
So the weight would be the total
volume of the iceberg

00:35:00.333 --> 00:35:02.467
times the density of ice.

00:35:02.467 --> 00:35:05.967
That product will give you
the mass in kilograms

00:35:05.967 --> 00:35:08.733
of the total iceberg.

00:35:08.733 --> 00:35:12.067
And then that's going to be
balanced by a buoyancy force

00:35:12.067 --> 00:35:16.433
pushing up, which is the volume
submerged it's only

00:35:16.433 --> 00:35:21.467
this part multiplied
by the density

00:35:21.467 --> 00:35:23.433
of the fluid displaced.

00:35:23.433 --> 00:35:26.433
Well, it's displacing
seawater.

00:35:26.433 --> 00:35:28.200
So we use the density
of seawater.

00:35:28.200 --> 00:35:32.367
So that's the statement
of equilibrium for

00:35:32.367 --> 00:35:35.700
this floating object.

00:35:35.700 --> 00:35:41.067
If I simply divide through,
I can get this expression.

00:35:41.067 --> 00:35:46.267
The ratio of the submerged part
of the iceberg to the

00:35:46.267 --> 00:35:50.833
total is simply going to be
dividing through the ratio of

00:35:50.833 --> 00:35:55.400
the two densities, rho ice
over rho of seawater.

00:35:55.400 --> 00:35:57.967
And we've already used
these values before.

00:35:57.967 --> 00:36:02.167
The density of ice is about 917
kilograms per cubic meter.

00:36:02.167 --> 00:36:05.300
Seawater, with the salt,
is about 1,025.

00:36:05.300 --> 00:36:06.833
Divide that out, you get 0.9.

00:36:06.833 --> 00:36:12.467
So the point is the ratio of
this part to the total is

00:36:12.467 --> 00:36:15.033
about 0.9, or 90%.

00:36:15.033 --> 00:36:24.067
So that is a solid derivation of
why it is that most of the

00:36:24.067 --> 00:36:27.167
iceberg is below sea
level there.

00:36:27.167 --> 00:36:28.400
Any questions on that?

00:36:33.100 --> 00:36:37.067
Now, a very interesting place on
the west coast of Greenland

00:36:37.067 --> 00:36:38.300
is Jacobshaven.

00:36:40.467 --> 00:36:43.500
So here is the ice sheet, the
Greenland Ice Sheet out to the

00:36:43.500 --> 00:36:48.800
east. There's Baffin Bay to
the west. And the glacier

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:49.800
comes down here.

00:36:49.800 --> 00:36:54.333
But here is indicated where
that calving front was in

00:36:54.333 --> 00:36:59.000
1851, 1875, and back to 2003.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:03.067
So it's been retreating
rather dramatically.

00:37:03.067 --> 00:37:05.200
But I want to make something
clear to you, that even when

00:37:05.200 --> 00:37:08.800
this retreats all the way back
here this is where the calving

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:11.833
is now taking place still,
this channel

00:37:11.833 --> 00:37:13.100
is choked with ice.

00:37:13.100 --> 00:37:15.067
It's not open water.

00:37:15.067 --> 00:37:17.867
It's got lots of icebergs
sitting in it, some of them

00:37:17.867 --> 00:37:19.167
making their way out.

00:37:19.167 --> 00:37:23.233
Some of them grounded and
kind of stuck there.

00:37:23.233 --> 00:37:25.867
But the calving front
is back there.

00:37:25.867 --> 00:37:29.300
So again the question is, is
this a significant change?

00:37:29.300 --> 00:37:32.867
If the channel with the fjord is
still choked with ice, does

00:37:32.867 --> 00:37:36.700
it make any difference whether
the calving is here or the

00:37:36.700 --> 00:37:39.000
calving is I would think it
would make a difference.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.867
Because again, if you're calving
back here, that's

00:37:41.867 --> 00:37:46.333
going to allow a faster flow
down from the ice sheet.

00:37:46.333 --> 00:37:49.167
You're going to be moving more
ice from the Greenland Ice

00:37:49.167 --> 00:37:52.433
Sheet if the calving is back
here than if it has to go all

00:37:52.433 --> 00:37:56.033
the way up here before
it can calve off.

00:37:56.033 --> 00:37:59.867
I was there last year and
took some pictures.

00:37:59.867 --> 00:38:02.600
There's nothing for scale here,
but that's about 40

00:38:02.600 --> 00:38:04.800
meters high.

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:08.067
And then when you think what
lies below that oh, and I'm

00:38:08.067 --> 00:38:09.500
looking across the channels.

00:38:09.500 --> 00:38:12.000
Through the little gap there
you can see the land on the

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:15.767
other side of that fjord.

00:38:15.767 --> 00:38:17.000
But those are pretty impressive

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.600
glaciers, just the part--

00:38:19.600 --> 00:38:22.200
icebergs, just the part
that are above water.

00:38:22.200 --> 00:38:24.300
Here's a small ship for scale.

00:38:24.300 --> 00:38:26.233
You can get some idea.

00:38:26.233 --> 00:38:28.867
Has anybody seen something like
this, traveled to high

00:38:28.867 --> 00:38:31.100
latitudes and seen something
like this?

00:38:31.100 --> 00:38:31.833
Where were you?

