PROFESSOR: Antarctica.

00:38:33.367 --> 00:38:33.867
Nice.

00:38:33.867 --> 00:38:35.633
Yes.

00:38:35.633 --> 00:38:40.433
So they look a bit different in
Antarctica, but the physics

00:38:40.433 --> 00:38:41.400
is the same.

00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:44.300
It depends on the shape of the
ice, how much it's crumpled as

00:38:44.300 --> 00:38:46.367
it comes down before
it breaks off.

00:38:46.367 --> 00:38:49.233
But basically, you've got the
same process happening in both

00:38:49.233 --> 00:38:50.467
hemispheres.

00:38:53.500 --> 00:38:56.033
The other reason I wanted to
show you this particular

00:38:56.033 --> 00:39:02.833
location, Jacobshaven, is that
there's good reason to think

00:39:02.833 --> 00:39:08.967
that it was a Jacobshaven
iceberg that sunk the Titanic.

00:39:08.967 --> 00:39:12.767
And I want to show you
the geometry of that.

00:39:12.767 --> 00:39:20.533
So here is Jacobshaven, on the
west coast of Greenland.

00:39:20.533 --> 00:39:25.067
And if an iceberg breaks off
there, it'll be carried first

00:39:25.067 --> 00:39:27.133
northward by the West
Greenland Current.

00:39:27.133 --> 00:39:29.467
Then at some point it'll get
drawn into the Labrador

00:39:29.467 --> 00:39:32.667
current, come down past
if it's large enough.

00:39:32.667 --> 00:39:34.533
It will be melting as it comes
down through here.

00:39:34.533 --> 00:39:37.933
But if it's large enough, it
will persist and possibly get

00:39:37.933 --> 00:39:44.333
down into this area south of 50
north, and maybe even south

00:39:44.333 --> 00:39:47.433
of 45 degrees north,
down in this area.

00:39:47.433 --> 00:39:51.233
And at that point now, it
becomes into the great circle

00:39:51.233 --> 00:39:57.600
route for ships between say
New York and England.

00:39:57.600 --> 00:40:04.967
And that's what the Titanic was
doing in April of 1912.

00:40:04.967 --> 00:40:07.467
It was making its way from
well, it started in

00:40:07.467 --> 00:40:12.233
Southampton, England, and was
making its way to New York.

00:40:12.233 --> 00:40:14.067
And that's where it hit
the iceberg and sunk.

00:40:14.067 --> 00:40:16.967
So almost certainly
it came from the

00:40:16.967 --> 00:40:18.100
west coast of Greenland.

00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:22.967
And because Jacobshaven is known
to be the most prolific

00:40:22.967 --> 00:40:27.933
generator of icebergs, I guess
it's a fair guess that it was

00:40:27.933 --> 00:40:31.933
one of those Jacobshaven
icebergs that was the one that

00:40:31.933 --> 00:40:36.500
did the deed for the Titanic.

00:40:36.500 --> 00:40:37.733
Any questions on that?

00:40:41.700 --> 00:40:44.800
Now we'll turn to mountain
glaciers.

00:40:44.800 --> 00:40:49.700
And there again, a bit like the
ice sheets, you have an

00:40:49.700 --> 00:40:53.700
accumulation zone and
an ablation zone.

00:40:53.700 --> 00:40:57.667
So every year, full 12 months
that goes by, you've added a

00:40:57.667 --> 00:41:00.233
bit of ice here.

00:41:00.233 --> 00:41:02.567
And that cannot continue.

00:41:02.567 --> 00:41:04.933
You've got to balance that
mass in some way.

00:41:04.933 --> 00:41:08.967
And that is eventually
balanced by a flow, a

00:41:08.967 --> 00:41:12.967
liquid-like flow down
the mountain slope

00:41:12.967 --> 00:41:14.367
by the glacier itself.

00:41:14.367 --> 00:41:19.333
Some of it is accomplished
by distorting the ice.

00:41:19.333 --> 00:41:22.267
And some of it is accomplished
by just sliding the ice along

00:41:22.267 --> 00:41:23.667
the bottom.

00:41:23.667 --> 00:41:26.467
But in any case, it is
moving under the

00:41:26.467 --> 00:41:29.167
influence of gravity.

00:41:29.167 --> 00:41:32.733
And then in some cases, it makes
it all the way down to

00:41:32.733 --> 00:41:34.167
the ocean surface.

