It actually has a
shear within it.

00:42:07.633 --> 00:42:09.533
Icebergs do--I'm sorry, glaciers
do some of this, but

00:42:09.533 --> 00:42:12.433
they also slip a little
bit along the base.

00:42:12.433 --> 00:42:14.667
So it would be more accurate
to draw it like this.

00:42:14.667 --> 00:42:17.067
There's some internal
deformation, but there's also

00:42:17.067 --> 00:42:18.900
some slip right at the bottom.

00:42:18.900 --> 00:42:23.067
So it's a combination of the
two that allows it to slide

00:42:23.067 --> 00:42:26.200
down the slope like that.

00:42:28.833 --> 00:42:29.333
Thanks for that.

00:42:29.333 --> 00:42:37.733
So in this case, for these two
glaciers in Alaska, they've

00:42:37.733 --> 00:42:40.400
actually made it all the
way down to sea level.

00:42:40.400 --> 00:42:41.700
This one easily.

00:42:41.700 --> 00:42:43.867
This one just barely.

00:42:43.867 --> 00:42:47.767
But any glacier that makes it
down to sea level is called a

00:42:47.767 --> 00:42:49.567
tidewater glacier.

00:42:49.567 --> 00:42:55.033
It makes it down, and then
partly because of the tides

00:42:55.033 --> 00:42:57.667
but it would happen anyway
you'll get calving, and you

00:42:57.667 --> 00:42:58.733
produce icebergs.

00:42:58.733 --> 00:43:02.867
So a tidewater glacier will
produce icebergs that will

00:43:02.867 --> 00:43:06.267
then float out over the sea.

00:43:06.267 --> 00:43:08.533
You're likely to have these
in high latitudes.

00:43:08.533 --> 00:43:10.367
Remember, you can have mountain
glaciers in low

00:43:10.367 --> 00:43:11.600
latitudes too.

00:43:14.333 --> 00:43:19.600
Mount Kilimanjaro in Africa,
almost exactly on the equator,

00:43:19.600 --> 00:43:21.567
has a glacier at the top.

00:43:21.567 --> 00:43:23.300
But it certainly doesn't
come down very far.

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:25.867
And it certainly does not reach
any ocean where you

00:43:25.867 --> 00:43:28.533
would produce icebergs.

00:43:28.533 --> 00:43:33.567
But these tidewater glaciers
do produce icebergs.

00:43:33.567 --> 00:43:36.000
Here's an example in Alaska
of one that does

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:37.433
not, Stevens Glacier.

00:43:37.433 --> 00:43:42.267
So you can see glaciers from
various parts of the mountain

00:43:42.267 --> 00:43:44.700
chain combining and merging.

00:43:44.700 --> 00:43:46.800
Here is the last merger
right here.

00:43:46.800 --> 00:43:49.700
But then there's the terminus
of the glacier.

00:43:49.700 --> 00:43:52.800
There is some melt water and
the river will carry that

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:54.033
water away to the sea.

00:43:54.033 --> 00:43:57.867
The water will get to the sea,
but not the ice itself.

00:43:57.867 --> 00:44:01.400
So this is happening
more and more.

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:04.500
As glaciers--as the climate
warms and glaciers retreat,

00:44:04.500 --> 00:44:06.400
their terminus moves
further up.

00:44:06.400 --> 00:44:09.300
But eventually that water,
of course, always

00:44:09.300 --> 00:44:12.067
returns to the sea.

00:44:15.067 --> 00:44:16.767
Very often you can
see the seam.

00:44:16.767 --> 00:44:19.500
Where two glaciers come together
you have a little bit

00:44:19.500 --> 00:44:21.633
of rock rubble.

00:44:21.633 --> 00:44:25.800
And in some glaciers you can
see way down at their snout

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:29.633
you can see five or six of
these little black lines.

00:44:29.633 --> 00:44:33.033
And if you trace them back, each
one of them originates at

00:44:33.033 --> 00:44:33.967
a point like this.

00:44:33.967 --> 00:44:38.233
So you can actually keep track
of all the tributaries by the

00:44:38.233 --> 00:44:45.100
little line of rock rubble that
gets permanently put into

00:44:45.100 --> 00:44:47.333
the glacier.

00:44:47.333 --> 00:44:48.500
Questions there?

00:44:50.500 --> 00:44:53.633
So again, the speed of these
things are quite slow.

00:44:53.633 --> 00:44:59.067
They might be only a few
centimeters per day or a few

00:44:59.067 --> 00:45:01.467
centimeters per week,
in some cases.

00:45:01.467 --> 00:45:05.767
But what they can do is drive
a stake here, go up on the

00:45:05.767 --> 00:45:08.433
bedrock, triangulate,
get the location.

00:45:08.433 --> 00:45:11.400
And then come back a week or
two later and see how much

00:45:11.400 --> 00:45:12.633
that stake has moved.

00:45:12.633 --> 00:45:15.467
And that will at least give you
the speed of the ice at

00:45:15.467 --> 00:45:16.933
the top of the glacier.

00:45:16.933 --> 00:45:19.500
It won't give you everything
you need to know about the

00:45:19.500 --> 00:45:21.733
depth all the way through,
the speed

00:45:21.733 --> 00:45:26.233
down through the glacier.

00:45:26.233 --> 00:45:31.033
Here's a couple of glaciers
from Norway.

00:45:33.667 --> 00:45:41.133
The word, well, "breen" simply
means ice or glacier, and so

00:45:41.133 --> 00:45:46.100
all the glaciers in Norway end
with the suffix "-breen." But

00:45:46.100 --> 00:45:49.800
there's the one in Briksdal,
and there's the one in Jenn

00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:51.667
and of course, "dal" just means
"valley" in Norwegian,

00:45:51.667 --> 00:45:56.100
so Jennsdals glacier and
Briks valley glacier.

00:45:56.100 --> 00:45:57.067
They're all named like that.

00:45:57.067 --> 00:46:03.200
But these are not tidewater
glaciers.

00:46:03.200 --> 00:46:04.300
This is not the sea.

00:46:04.300 --> 00:46:07.467
This is a little lake at the
bottom of the glacier, a

00:46:07.467 --> 00:46:08.733
freshwater lake.

00:46:08.733 --> 00:46:11.967
And it has that milky appearance
to it because

00:46:11.967 --> 00:46:15.500
underneath the glacier, where
there's a grinding process

00:46:15.500 --> 00:46:20.267
going on, you're developing
a kind of powder from the

00:46:20.267 --> 00:46:21.367
grinding of rock.

00:46:21.367 --> 00:46:22.900
And that ends up in the water.

00:46:22.900 --> 00:46:26.100
And then if you see that river,
even miles away, it'll

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:30.200
have that characteristic
milky appearance.

00:46:30.200 --> 00:46:32.433
And you can say, that one
came from a glacier.

00:46:32.433 --> 00:46:36.533
That river water came from a
glacier, because it has that

00:46:36.533 --> 00:46:40.600
so-called glacial milk and it's
characteristic of water

00:46:40.600 --> 00:46:43.733
that flows out from a mountain
glacier like that.

00:46:46.367 --> 00:46:49.600
Questions there?

00:46:49.600 --> 00:46:51.233
Here's another one.

00:46:51.233 --> 00:46:54.500
You can see the terminus of that
and the water rushing out

00:46:54.500 --> 00:46:58.333
from underneath in
that stream.

00:47:03.167 --> 00:47:07.000
We are, let's see, yeah...
I guess we'll quit here

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:09.567
and just finish up.

00:47:09.567 --> 00:47:12.467
There's just a little bit left
on ice, but I want to do a

00:47:12.467 --> 00:47:13.133
good job on that.

